          "body": "The first oracle (vv. 7-15) targets a theological error rather than a moral one. God does not reprove for the frequency of sacrifice (v. 8) — Israel's burnt offerings are 'continually before Me.' The problem is what Israel thinks the sacrifice accomplishes. By demolishing the idea that He could possibly need their bulls or their goats (vv. 9-13), God exposes the underlying assumption: that sacrifice is a mechanism for maintaining or appeasing a deity with appetites like their own. Every beast of the forest is already His; the world and its fullness are already His; if He were hungry He would not need to inform them (vv. 10-12). No offering they bring adds to His estate. The prescribed alternative in verses 14-15 retains sacrificial vocabulary but transforms its meaning entirely: *todah* (thanksgiving), vow-fulfillment, and prayer in the day of trouble are what He actually seeks — personal, dependent engagement rather than material transaction."
