          "title": "The psalm's theology of sacrifice — from transaction to thanksgiving",
          "body": "Psalm 50 is one of the Old Testament's most penetrating theologies of sacrifice, and its argument must be read carefully to avoid misunderstanding. Asaph does not abolish sacrifice — he redefines it. The word *todah* (thanksgiving offering, vv. 14, 23) was itself a specific sacrificial category in the Levitical system (Lev. 7:12-15); the psalm is not moving from sacrifice to non-sacrifice but from the wrong kind of sacrifice to the right kind. The thanksgiving sacrifice required the worshiper to come with a story — a specific act of divine rescue — and to declare it publicly before the congregation. It was inherently relational and testimonial, not transactional. Alongside todah, verse 14 requires the fulfillment of vows and verse 15 requires prayer in trouble followed by glory given to God. The whole package is a portrait of a worshiper who knows his dependence, recalls specific divine acts, fulfills his spoken commitments, and calls out to God in crisis. Calvin, commenting on verse 14, notes that 'God does not require external ceremonies for their own sake, but as helps to faith and piety — and when they are separated from these they are nothing but corruption.'"
